# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: airline-chicken
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:airline-chicken/afritada] The name *afritada* is derived from Spanish *fritada* ("fried"), referring to the first step of the preparation in which the meat is pan-fried before simmering in the tomato sauce.
[src:airline-chicken/afritada] Filipino *menudo* and *kaldereta* both use tomato sauce or banana ketchup.
[src:airline-chicken/afritada] However, *menudo* includes sliced liver, while *kaldereta* exclusively uses goat meat or occasionally beef.
[src:airline-chicken/afritada] *Igado* contains liver but no tomato sauce.
[src:airline-chicken/airline-chicken] The name of the cut is variously attributed to the shape resembling an airplane wing or that, because the exposed bone could be used as a handle to pick up the entire piece and eat it out of hand, it made it easier to eat in-flight.
[src:airline-chicken/airline-chicken] The cut is also known as a *Frenched breast*, due to the end of the wing bone being trimmed or Frenched, or chicken supreme.
[src:airline-chicken/airline-chicken] It is also known as Statler chicken, a name that originated from the Statler Hotel Boston, built in 1927 by E.M.
[src:airline-chicken/andong-jjimdak] There are many speculations on the origin of the dish.
[src:airline-chicken/andong-jjimdak] One is that it is a specialty food of the inner rich village of Andong during the Joseon period, prepared and eaten for special occasions.
[src:airline-chicken/andong-jjimdak] Another assumption is that during the 1980s in the *Dak golmok* (닭골목, literally "chicken alley") of the "Andong Gu Market," restaurant owners there made a dish including ingredients that regulars demanded, which became the current *Andong-jjimdak*.
[src:airline-chicken/andong-jjimdak] The most plausible speculation among existing assumptions is that merchants of the *Dak golmok* at the market created the dish to keep their position against the rapid expansion of Western fried chicken shops.
[src:airline-chicken/andong-jjimdak] Since *Andong-jjimdak* is cooked over high heat, it has less fat and can have various tastes by adding diverse ingredients according to recipe.
[src:airline-chicken/andong-jjimdak] It is popular among students and blue-collar workers due to the abundant portions compared to the price (generally around 20,000 won).
[src:airline-chicken/andong-jjimdak] *Andong-jjimdak* is also considered a nutritious dish due to the high protein content from the chicken, and various vitamins provided by the vegetables in the dish.
[src:airline-chicken/andong-jjimdak] To make the dish, the broth is prepared first by boiling a cleaned chopped chicken, whole garlic, onions, ginger and a type of fresh green chili pepper called "Cheongyang gochu" (청양고추) altogether in a pot.
[src:airline-chicken/andong-jjimdak] The pepper is famous for its extreme spiciness and plays an important role in tasting the dish.
[src:airline-chicken/andong-jjimdak] The cooked chicken is simmered with a sauce made from *ganjang*, *mullyeot* (물엿, syrup-like condiment), sugar, and pepper in the broth.
[src:airline-chicken/andong-jjimdak] Slices of shiitake, and diced carrots, potatoes, and other vegetables are added in the pot and boiled over high heat for ten minutes.
[src:airline-chicken/andong-jjimdak] Whilst the carrots and potatoes are almost getting cooked, a little amount of wheat flour and spinach, sliced cucumber, scallions and the noodles are added to the pot as well.
[src:airline-chicken/andong-jjimdak] After cooking, the dish is put on a plate and sesame seeds are spread over it.
[src:airline-chicken/arroz-caldo] The Spanish name *arroz caldo* is translated as "rice broth".
[src:airline-chicken/arroz-caldo] It originally referred to all types of rice gruels (Tagalog: *lugaw*), but has come to refer to a specific type of *lugaw* that uses chicken and is heavily infused with ginger.
[src:airline-chicken/arroz-caldo] Philippine Airlines is known particularly for its **arroz caldo**, reportedly a favorite of President Corazon Aquino.
[src:airline-chicken/arroz-caldo] In Visayan regions, savory *lugaw* is known as *pospas*.
[src:airline-chicken/arroz-caldo] Chicken *pospas* is regarded as the direct equivalent of **arroz caldo**.
[src:airline-chicken/arroz-caldo] However, unlike **arroz caldo**, **pospas** traditionally does not use safflower.
[src:airline-chicken/arroz-caldo] A much rarer variant of **arroz caldo** is *arroz caldong palaka*, which uses frog legs (*palaka* is Tagalog for "frog").
[src:airline-chicken/arroz-caldo] Non-traditional variants include vegan versions, which use mushrooms or tofu instead of meat.
[src:airline-chicken/arroz-con-pollo] There is some debate as to whether it originated in Spain or Puerto Rico.
[src:airline-chicken/arroz-con-pollo] Many Puerto Ricans note that arroz con pollo cannot be made without beer and annatto oil, and saffron is no substitute.
[src:airline-chicken/arroz-con-pollo] Beer and annatto are rarely used in Spanish cooking and never in arroz con pollo there.
[src:airline-chicken/arroz-con-pollo] Annatto is frequently used in Puerto Rican cooking especially in rice dishes like arroz con gandules (rice with pork and pigeon peas) and arroz con maiz (rice with corn and sausage).
[src:airline-chicken/arroz-con-pollo] Beer is used in many Puerto Rican dishes like pollo guisado (braised stewed chicken) and asopao de pollo (chicken rice stew).
[src:airline-chicken/arroz-con-pollo] Many Puerto Rican rice dishes are generously seasoned with sofrito, a sauce commonly used in arroz con pollo.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-bakar] In 2023, TasteAtlas ranked Indonesian grilled chicken, 'Ayam Bakar', as one of the best traditional chicken dishes in the world.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-bakar] In Java, the chicken is usually marinated with a mixture of *kecap manis* (sweet soy sauce) and coconut oil, applied with a brush during grilling.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-bakar] The *bumbu* spice mixture may vary among regions, but usually it consists of a combination of ground shallot, garlic, chili pepper, coriander, tamarind juice, candlenut, turmeric, galangal, and salt.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-bakar] The chicken pieces are usually partially cooked in the spice mixture using a small fire before grilling for the chicken to absorb the spices.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-bakar] During the grilling process, the remaining spices are applied upon the chicken.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-bakar] Ayam bakar is usually served with *sambal terasi* (chilli with *terasi*) or *sambal kecap* (sliced chilli and shallot in sweet soy sauce) as dipping sauce or condiment and slices of cucumber and tomato as garnishing.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-bakar] There are many recipes of *ayam bakar*, among the popular ones are Padang-style ayam bakar, *ayam percik* and *ayam golek* from Malaysia, *ayam bakar Taliwang* of Lombok island, Sundanese *bakakak hayam*, and Javanese *ayam bakar bumbu rujak* (grilled spicy coconut chicken).
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-bakar] Usually, the chicken is marinated with mixture of spice pastes, sometimes kecap manis (sweet soy sauce), and then grilled.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-bumbu-rujak] Rujak seasoning can be used not only for chicken, but also for grilled fish, grilled duck, and others.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-bumbu-rujak] Ayam bumbu rujak originates from East Java.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-bumbu-rujak] Its popularity has grown to various regions in Indonesia and has become favorite food for many people and circles.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-bumbu-rujak] After processing, rujak seasoning becomes spicy, savoury and sweet, producing a unique taste in chicken dishes.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-goreng] In 2024, TasteAtlas ranked *ayam goreng* as one of the best fried chicken dishes and the best traditional chicken dishes in the world.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-goreng] Some versions of *ayam goreng* coat chicken in neither batter or flour, but instead seasoned richly with various spices.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-goreng] The spice mixture varies by regions, but usually consists of a combination of ground shallot, garlic, Indian bay leaves, turmeric, lemongrass, tamarind juice, candlenut, galangal, salt, and sugar.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-goreng] The chicken pieces are marinated in the spice mixture prior to frying, sometimes heating the chicken in ground spices.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-goreng] Most often prior to deep frying, *ayam goreng* is already half-cooked with yellowish colour tinted of turmeric.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-goreng] In Javanese, this process is called *ungkep*.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-goreng] The chicken is then deep fried in an ample amount of hot cooking oil, either palm or coconut oil.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-goreng] The chicken is fried until golden yellow.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-goreng] Some variants such as Javanese *ayam goreng kremes* add the deep fried spiced flour as crispy granules.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-goreng] While in other recipes, these granules are acquired from fried grated galangal or coconut (*serundeng*).
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-goreng] In Indonesia and Malaysia various style of foreign fried chicken is often also called as *ayam goreng*.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-goreng] Common Southern United States fried chicken is often called *ayam goreng tepung* or flour-battered or breaded fried chicken.
[src:airline-chicken/ayam-goreng] Common McDonald's fried chicken is marketed as "Ayam Goreng McD" in Malaysia.
